		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=71614"><span id=>Eitsekur</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br><img src=/shared/user_star_ico.gif height=9 width=9><br>119 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [3.50]</nobr><br><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Eitsekur&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>I have responded to a lot of posts, but haven't asked questions too much, so here goes:<br><br>I am somewhat confused as to what role the high-level Shadow Knight plays.&nbsp;&nbsp;I hear that they make good pullers, but usually monks are the main pullers if there is one present in the group.  They cannot tank as well as a warrior in most cases, as I understand.  Their DOTs, lifetaps, and debuffs seem to be marginally useful at best, though they are useful in taunting in my experience.  They deal damage, but again, never as much damage as a rogue or monk can.  I understand that in tandem all these abilites make the Shadow Knight an excellent class, but I think my confusion is that I cannot see what we are supposed to be doing with all these abilities besides sitting there and hitting the mob(s).  If anyone can elaborate on the Shadow Knight role in a good group, and in raid situations as well, I would highly appreciate it, as I wish to be adequately equipped to serve a purpose in higher-level groups.  Thanks for your input (and don't construe any of my statements as a lack of appreciation for being an SK, which I absolutely love).<br><br>Eitsekur Eitfyndir<br>28 Shadow Knight (Erudite)<br>Heartbinder's Heroes, 7th Hammer</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >3 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
